02:36:13.660 --> 02:36:18.540
to love each other and be, be, be real partners. We're here because our countries demand that we

02:36:18.540 --> 02:36:23.760
put aside some of our differences and cooperating meaningful ways for the security of our countries.

02:36:23.760 --> 02:36:30.680
That was when Yeltsin had just emerged. There was the hope then, right? But it was a realism

02:36:30.680 --> 02:36:35.140
attached, he attached to it. That was very important, needed to make it real. Because if

02:36:35.140 --> 02:36:39.740
otherwise you would have, you know, been pretending and playing games, which there's no point to play

02:36:39.740 --> 02:36:45.840
games. If you're arch enemies, you just do what you need to do. So a year later, it all culminated

02:36:45.840 --> 02:36:51.680
in this coup in Moscow when hardliners tried to overthrow Yeltsin. But the one thing it showed is that

02:36:51.680 --> 02:36:57.960
at a time of extreme need, we could work with the Russians because we had a common interest to keep

02:36:57.960 --> 02:37:03.580
Yeltsin in power. Russian intelligence decided they weren't ready to overthrow Yeltsin through force

02:37:03.580 --> 02:37:11.640
and violence. They ended up doing that. This is 93, it was eight years later, of course, when Vladimir

02:37:11.640 --> 02:37:18.340
Putin came to power, legally, the right way, if you want to call it that. And the Russians don't like coups

02:37:18.340 --> 02:37:23.140
and violence any more than we would like in our own country. So we worked together. And it was

02:37:23.140 --> 02:37:28.160
astonishing. I didn't know when I first called Russian intelligence chief and said, hey, we need

02:37:28.160 --> 02:37:33.200
help. We need you to protect us. It looks like we're going to be taken hostage. When I was leading a

02:37:33.200 --> 02:37:40.920
detachment of people outside the embassy and coming under fire from coup plotters, snipers and things,

02:37:41.480 --> 02:37:46.020
I called them for help. And I didn't expect any help. In fact, it was the ambassador at the time,

02:37:46.020 --> 02:37:50.600
ambassador Tom Pickering. He's the one who's, I called him in desperation, say, there's no way

02:37:50.600 --> 02:37:54.280
you can help us, is there? Because I, because of the embassy, all, everybody in the embassy was

02:37:54.280 --> 02:37:59.740
underground in the, in the embassy compound, except for us. We're out doing reporting and things like

02:37:59.740 --> 02:38:03.980
that to tell Washington what was going on. Otherwise they wouldn't have known anything going on at the

02:38:03.980 --> 02:38:08.320
time. All the news networks had shut down and- And you end up like holed up in an abandoned

02:38:08.320 --> 02:38:12.060
building or something? Well, we, we holed up, everything was abandoned, but we were in the ambassador's

02:38:12.060 --> 02:38:17.880
residence, which we opened up and used just for, as a command post, which I think that started as

02:38:17.880 --> 02:38:22.960
five of us. I think we ended up with seven or eight long. I put the whole, like all the details

02:38:22.960 --> 02:38:28.280
in that. I was a little surprised that again, it was nice to see they, they had no problem with

02:38:28.280 --> 02:38:32.580
telling that story. Cause I think it's important that I, the, the purpose of the story and the purpose

02:38:32.580 --> 02:38:40.140
of me describing it is that, you know, intelligence is almost always unexpected and it's, it's greatest

02:38:40.140 --> 02:38:49.600
value is proven in the most difficult times pro and con. And, and you, you can't fear or avoid

02:38:49.600 --> 02:38:56.980
the difficult circumstances. You have to kind of run into them and embrace the, the, the difficulty.

02:38:56.980 --> 02:39:03.020
So they, they ended up sending a team to protect us from being taken hostage. And the only rules we

02:39:03.020 --> 02:39:07.680
had, I'll never forget the phone call from the director. He said, okay, Rolf, there's very

02:39:07.680 --> 02:39:13.220
extraordinary circumstances. We're going to send you a team of heavily armed guys to try to keep you

02:39:13.220 --> 02:39:20.700
from getting captured. But here's the deal. One is do not commingle. Our guys and your guys are

02:39:20.700 --> 02:39:26.100
separate. We'll do our work outside your perimeter or whatever. So don't mix. And he goes, if you are

02:39:26.100 --> 02:39:31.620
stormed or they take, get in a firefight or whatever happens, die in your separate foxholes.

02:39:31.620 --> 02:39:38.840
And he didn't have to explain why he, cause however that day turned out in Russian history,

02:39:38.840 --> 02:39:45.640
didn't want to leave any evidence of who would work with whom along the way. Cause it was in doubt.

02:39:45.640 --> 02:39:50.820
I, I, the one thing I learned personally in a way that helped me even with the spiritual stuff later,

02:39:51.420 --> 02:39:57.580
miss this mystical experiences is history is not inevitable. History isn't, history comes together

02:39:57.580 --> 02:40:04.360
because of the decisions people make. And when you're experiencing it live, like in a war or in

02:40:04.360 --> 02:40:09.640
a coup or in a change of government, you realize it could go that way. If these things are done and

02:40:09.640 --> 02:40:14.920
goes that way, if another thing is done. You've been in the room with Vladimir Putin,

02:40:15.440 --> 02:40:20.900
what's your impression of him? Well, it wasn't as extensive as so many of the people,

02:40:21.060 --> 02:40:26.280
you know, obviously in the U S government who have had a lot of interaction with them. So I don't want

02:40:26.280 --> 02:40:31.660
to put it on. So I just happened to have a fairly unique one-time thing where we met in his first

02:40:31.660 --> 02:40:36.900
foreign trip. I was in Norway. I'm Norwegian American, as I said, so it was a great honor for

02:40:36.900 --> 02:40:41.620
me to go back to Norway. And I happened to be there again, one of these things I thank God a

02:40:41.620 --> 02:40:47.280
little bit for the privilege of to be there during the last meeting of what was called the Oslo peace

02:40:47.280 --> 02:40:54.500
accord process was started in Oslo, Norway and now was culminating. So this was, uh, in the November

02:40:54.500 --> 02:41:06.240
19, 93, 93, no, no, 1998, 1998, the last meeting. Oh, okay. And, uh, the last meeting was one amazing.

02:41:06.240 --> 02:41:15.120
No, no, I had no role of any appreciable, nothing. I was there as, as literally a appreciation gift.

02:41:15.460 --> 02:41:18.880
Some, I knew the prime minister and other people in the Norwegian government, they said,

02:41:19.400 --> 02:41:24.060
invite, invite me and my wife to the, to the dinner. But at the dinner was president Clinton

02:41:24.060 --> 02:41:32.720
came of course, um, Vladimir Putin's first foreign trip as prime minister. And then, um,

02:41:32.720 --> 02:41:38.340
of course, the main ones, Yasser Arafat and Ehud Barak, who was the prime minister of,

02:41:38.340 --> 02:41:44.880
of Israel at the time. Now I had never met Arafat, Ehud Barak. I had met Clinton just,

02:41:45.040 --> 02:41:50.740
you know, kind of like formalistically, uh, but, and Putin. And, and I got to see them all in this

02:41:50.740 --> 02:41:55.360
kind of, as an observer vantage point where if anything, anybody would say, well, who's this guy?

02:41:55.780 --> 02:41:59.840
Cause everybody there was more important than me. Literally everybody at the, at the dinner,

02:41:59.840 --> 02:42:06.340
but that was great. I, there was no pressure. I could literally just observe, uh, Putin and

02:42:06.340 --> 02:42:11.580
others. And it was just amazing. I was, there was a moment when, after dinner, when everybody got up

02:42:11.580 --> 02:42:16.580
and mingled, went to the King's library to visit the castle in his library to have cognac and

02:42:16.580 --> 02:42:20.800
chocolates. And everybody's walking there and I'm going to catch everything on the way. And I see

02:42:20.800 --> 02:42:27.360
Clinton literally grab Arafat in the middle of the room. And Clinton was, whatever one thinks of him

02:42:27.360 --> 02:42:30.200
political. That's not what I'm talking about here. He had a presence, right?

02:42:30.380 --> 02:42:33.680
Oh, well, everybody says that everybody says the most charismatic guy.

02:42:33.860 --> 02:42:37.160
He just had a natural charisma. He didn't do anything. He just stands there. Right.

02:42:37.280 --> 02:42:37.480
Sure.

02:42:37.640 --> 02:42:43.360
So he grabs Arafat who also in his weird way had a charisma to a presence, right? Cause he's

02:42:43.880 --> 02:42:51.320
the iconic head wrap and et cetera. And he says to Arafat, take the deal. Yes, sir. Take the deal.

02:42:51.320 --> 02:42:57.400
It's your last best chance for peace. And I remember listening to that thing. Wow. So like

02:42:57.400 --> 02:43:03.560
important, but I just heard, I thought it's very important. And I just felt so depressed as I knew

02:43:03.560 --> 02:43:09.540
it was no, no, no, no, you know, foreshadowing or future. I just like instinctively, my gut was all

02:43:09.540 --> 02:43:12.940
this is not going to turn out well. And of course it's turned out terribly.

02:43:13.400 --> 02:43:18.420
Well, it's turned out terribly. I mean, partially. Yes, sir. Arafat would speak out of both sides

02:43:18.420 --> 02:43:22.300
of his mouth and he would speak to his own population, say certain things and then speak

02:43:22.300 --> 02:43:28.120
to the West and say other things, but also Yitzhak Rabin also, uh, you know, taken out

02:43:28.120 --> 02:43:34.340
by, by his own, you know, people and Haredi, you know, Jews who are just really extremists

02:43:34.340 --> 02:43:39.820
and wanted, you know, to cede nothing at all costs. And, you know, I think in, in many

02:43:39.820 --> 02:43:46.660
ways that whole, the middle East, you know, uh, conundrum quagmire has been, has been

02:43:46.660 --> 02:43:50.940
so stuck for so long and maybe we, you know, maybe we've made a little bit of progress in

02:43:50.940 --> 02:43:56.360
the last year, but it's been so, so stuck, uh, because of kind of extremists on, on both

02:43:56.360 --> 02:44:00.600
sides and because in many ways the incentives of the leaders are to like actually maintain

02:44:00.600 --> 02:44:06.880
the conflict. Yeah. So unfortunate. It is. It is. It's a factory of, yeah. Well, my, my,

02:44:06.880 --> 02:44:12.460
my, but then watching Putin, just to the point of your, your question was I already had the

02:44:12.460 --> 02:44:19.780
impression that he would be more consequential than I thought he might at the time by any

02:44:19.780 --> 02:44:24.400
standard of reasoning or what I knew about him. I, but I just had, he had the presence

02:44:24.400 --> 02:44:29.280
too. He was boring, the gray man on the corner, but that in itself impressed me because he

02:44:29.280 --> 02:44:34.100
wasn't trying to fit in. He wasn't trying to like speak loudly to be heard. He, he was

02:44:34.100 --> 02:44:40.560
way too self-assured, you know, for, for that kind of a reaction to the situation. And I

02:44:40.560 --> 02:44:44.960
respected that. I thought, okay, this guy could end up being way more of his own man

02:44:44.960 --> 02:44:51.320
than we, we think he might be going into that time period. One last thing on, on the, cause

02:44:51.320 --> 02:44:57.140
it's, it's ties to Russia and the Middle East again, five years earlier, 1993 again, after

02:44:57.140 --> 02:45:01.680
the coup and all that, I was meeting with the Russians. Yevgeny Primakov is his name. He

02:45:01.680 --> 02:45:05.640
was the head of Russian intelligence. I got to know him very, very well. He was, we'd meet

02:45:05.640 --> 02:45:09.780
almost every week and had all kinds of discussions about everything. We've talked almost like

02:45:09.780 --> 02:45:13.540
we are, Jesse, about all kinds of big subjects. And he was a guy who felt very comfortable.

02:45:13.720 --> 02:45:18.020
I thought he was a brilliant, brilliant man, actually. And he probably would have been

02:45:18.020 --> 02:45:25.920
a prime minister before, instead of Putin in the mid nineties, after Yeltsin left, had

02:45:25.920 --> 02:45:33.320
he not passed away from health problems and old age, et cetera. But at the time he was always

02:45:33.320 --> 02:45:38.380
musing with me about what, what can we do to be serious people? There's a Russian expression,

02:45:38.540 --> 02:45:42.380
serious, not a Russian. It's the most important thing to a Russian. It can love you or hate

02:45:42.380 --> 02:45:48.100
you, but you got to be a serious, a serious person, serious professional, serious about

02:45:48.100 --> 02:45:53.180
what you do. Don't give me bullshit. And he says, you know, we got to do something, but

02:45:53.180 --> 02:45:57.880
I can think of one thing that would be unbelievable if we could find a way to do it. I said, what's

02:45:57.880 --> 02:46:05.040
that? He said, well, you have your means, meaning CIA. We have our means, meaning the SVR, which

02:46:05.040 --> 02:46:10.240
is the foreign intelligence component of Russian intelligence. And we have them in the Middle

02:46:10.240 --> 02:46:14.540
East. So let's apply all our efforts in the Middle East where we really need something

02:46:14.540 --> 02:46:23.460
to happen to break this longstanding stalemate problem. Our goal will be to keep Arafat alive.

02:46:23.460 --> 02:46:32.180
Your goal will be to keep Rabin alive. And I thought it was genius. Of course, I sent it

02:46:32.180 --> 02:46:37.680
in and everybody thought I was insane. And I never got a good explanation as to why it

02:46:37.680 --> 02:46:40.840
really wasn't even considered. Maybe you just offered it.

02:46:41.400 --> 02:46:47.740
Yeah. Yeah. Right. Yeah. It's tough. I mean, I mean, we've talked about this, you know,

02:46:47.740 --> 02:46:52.140
too, in our last interview, you know, where, you know, people always talk about a deep state

02:46:52.140 --> 02:46:56.880
and, you know, it's, I think clearly there is no sort of cabal in a back room smoking

02:46:56.880 --> 02:47:01.600
cigars or something, but there are, there is, not only is it conspiracy to say that there

02:47:01.600 --> 02:47:05.220
are all sorts of misaligned incentives when it comes to big bureaucracies and that's any

02:47:05.220 --> 02:47:11.720
institution. And so, yeah, no, just going back to like, you know, why would somebody senselessly

02:47:11.720 --> 02:47:16.280
say no to a thing like that? Or, you know, I, I am sympathetic to a lot of the John Mearsheimer

02:47:16.280 --> 02:47:20.340
arguments as well that like, you know, we've totally reneged on Putin a million different

02:47:20.340 --> 02:47:25.040
times and, you know, we've, we've encroached a lot on, on, you know, their, their territory

02:47:25.040 --> 02:47:30.860
and, you know, not, not to at all, you know, uh, uh, apologize for a lot of his wrongdoings,

02:47:30.860 --> 02:47:36.240
which are very real, but, um, yeah, there's, there's the, the incentives are often wrong in

02:47:36.240 --> 02:47:41.740
these organizations. Well, when you talk about people like Mearsheimer or others who try to

02:47:41.740 --> 02:47:46.680
express a different way of thinking of our policies and their impact, I mean, there's,

02:47:46.760 --> 02:47:51.160
there's a utility in those points of views. I don't agree with him on a lot of things, but

02:47:51.160 --> 02:47:55.820
I think he should be saying some of the things he's saying and it's helpful. The biggest thing

02:47:55.820 --> 02:48:03.700
we habitually do wrong in terms of follow through on policy, some of our policy ideas aren't so bad,

02:48:03.700 --> 02:48:09.100
but it's usually the, the huge flaws in the implementation usually. And, and it's not so

02:48:09.100 --> 02:48:13.640
much the underlining motives that line up with as much as people think they do with sort of deep

02:48:13.640 --> 02:48:19.480
state agendas. It's just either a mixture of incompetence or I'd say more the idea that we,

02:48:19.960 --> 02:48:24.740
we mirror image too much. So our biggest problem in understanding, for example, the Russians.

02:48:25.240 --> 02:48:32.380
Now, what I'm saying is not acceptable. It's not accepted, uh, thinking, but it's widely accepted,

02:48:32.380 --> 02:48:36.540
but some people understand it is our biggest mistake is not seeing things through their eyes

02:48:36.540 --> 02:48:41.800
and it doesn't justify what they're doing or thinking, but it's understanding it.

02:48:42.620 --> 02:48:47.180
And if you want to know why we are where we are with the Russians, you have to understand,

02:48:47.440 --> 02:48:52.400
see the world through their eyes. It doesn't mean you accept that view or more importantly,

02:48:52.400 --> 02:48:57.500
what they do is a consequence of what they feel, but at least understand why you're there and don't

02:48:57.500 --> 02:49:04.280
be surprised about it. Isn't there a, uh, Kenan quote about understanding the Russians or something?

02:49:04.280 --> 02:49:08.660
It's like, once you ascend to the top of the mountain, you know, you, you end up equally

02:49:08.660 --> 02:49:14.000
confused as to the Russian motive motivation or something. I'm totally paraphrasing and botching

02:49:14.000 --> 02:49:18.240
this, but there's something like that. I don't remember that, but I, I suspect, yeah. It's like,

02:49:18.260 --> 02:49:22.840
they're always mystical, confusing. There's no way to ultimately understand what they're up to or

02:49:22.840 --> 02:49:27.920
something, which feels somewhat right. You like, you know, the, the idea of a pull at borough is

02:49:27.920 --> 02:49:34.020
like this, you know, concealed, sealed off hermetically, you know, uh, enclosed sort of

02:49:34.020 --> 02:49:39.160
organization that, you know, you can never fully sort of understand. And Putin's always keeping the

02:49:39.160 --> 02:49:45.500
people around him on his, on their toes. And so it's this really hard kind of hermeneutic game of

02:49:45.500 --> 02:49:50.120
reading the tea leaves at all times with, you know, governments like that.

02:49:50.120 --> 02:49:55.440
I think you read tea leaves and see everything as being unscrutable when you don't have any real

02:49:55.440 --> 02:50:01.180
depth in either living in the country or having enough experience with the people of the country

02:50:01.180 --> 02:50:05.640
where you can understand where they're coming from. One of the biggest mistake we make with Russia or

02:50:05.640 --> 02:50:10.540
Xi Jinping in China or anybody for that matter, all the leaders, even some of our friend, friendly

02:50:10.540 --> 02:50:19.460
countries is, is, uh, not understanding that the country's not the leader. So the thing I'll never

02:50:19.460 --> 02:50:25.860
do is think of Russia as Vladimir Putin. I've read too much, many, too much Russian history,

02:50:26.000 --> 02:50:32.580
philosophy, uh, gotten into Russia. I've known too many Russians. I lived in Russia for, for enough

02:50:32.580 --> 02:50:38.160
years where I think of Russia first as the people, right? And then you can assess what Putin's doing.

02:50:38.160 --> 02:50:43.920
And the most important way you need to assess it is not what impact it has on the U S but what impact

02:50:43.920 --> 02:50:48.740
is it, what he's doing, having on the Russian people. Now I would make an argument that what's

02:50:48.740 --> 02:50:56.820
happening now is very damaging to the future interests of ordinary Russians. The same way I

02:50:56.820 --> 02:51:03.500
might assess what different presidents impact has on America. I don't, I don't care so much about

02:51:03.500 --> 02:51:09.840
how the president's policies affect the stock market as I do how the president's policies affect

02:51:09.840 --> 02:51:14.160
ordinary Americans. So I think we have to look at foreign countries the same way.

02:51:14.500 --> 02:51:20.880
If you look at China's meteoric rise in the 20th century, you're not compelled to think of China

02:51:20.880 --> 02:51:27.120
as an enemy or right, deep rival and everything that's progress in China is being antithetical to

02:51:27.120 --> 02:51:33.700
our interests. Look what they've done for the Chinese people over in a remarkable period of

02:51:33.700 --> 02:51:38.700
time. That's not all good, obviously, but start from a more solid basis to understand why the

02:51:38.700 --> 02:51:45.120
leaders do what they do in their own history, traditions, culture, environments, and religion.

02:51:45.280 --> 02:51:50.940
If you look at the reason I've always said, and a lot of Russia experts disagree with me on this,

02:51:50.940 --> 02:51:58.920
I've always said Russia can't embrace, cannot be a democracy like the United States. The Yeltsin

02:51:58.920 --> 02:52:02.860
years were a mirage. They weren't a missed opportunity. There was never an opportunity

02:52:02.860 --> 02:52:09.660
for Russia to go West. Even when famously, you know, Peter the Great talked about Western

02:52:09.660 --> 02:52:14.920
orientation, it had nothing to do in the context we would like to ascribe it to, like he wanted to be

02:52:14.920 --> 02:52:20.820
more connected culturally, et cetera, with the U.S. Russia is what Russia is, which is a deeply

02:52:20.820 --> 02:52:27.700
orthodox, homogeneous country with a very rich history and very rich, they're very smart people,

02:52:27.800 --> 02:52:32.540
they're very educated people. And they want what they want. They don't want what we want.

02:52:32.800 --> 02:52:32.920
Yeah.

02:52:33.380 --> 02:52:39.680
And I think that's a big mistake of what we try to impose, not so much our, any way of controlling

02:52:39.680 --> 02:52:42.940
countries, but our idea of imposing our culture.

02:52:42.940 --> 02:52:48.120
For sure. Well, they had, you know, under Gorbachev, you know, last leader of the USSR that

02:52:48.120 --> 02:52:54.820
disbanded it. You had Glasnost and you had Perestroika, and you had, you know, open minds

02:52:54.820 --> 02:53:00.780
make open markets or whatever. And, or open markets make open minds, right? And I think

02:53:00.780 --> 02:53:07.880
what a lot of neoliberals sort of like miscalculated is that you'd inevitably, you'd get this like opening

02:53:07.880 --> 02:53:12.980
up of markets and then, you know, you'd end up with all of the amazing things about liberal

02:53:12.980 --> 02:53:17.940
democracy in the West, you know, in, in both China and Russia. And that's just not happened

02:53:17.940 --> 02:53:23.720
at all. And like, it took us a long time to, I think, update on that. You know, it was this

02:53:23.720 --> 02:53:28.960
neoconservative sort of hubris of like, you know, this would just happen on its own. And

02:53:28.960 --> 02:53:33.400
that's just not, you also have things like, you know, with Putin, I think there's this guy,

02:53:33.400 --> 02:53:39.840
Vladislav Surkov, who I think, you know, is this advisor who wrote this book, Almost Zero.

02:53:40.300 --> 02:53:45.040
And it's like all about like performance art and how that has to play into like your, you know,

02:53:45.180 --> 02:53:51.720
your, how you do politics. And so it's, I just find it so fascinating, you know, that whole,

02:53:51.820 --> 02:53:56.540
that whole world, it's just so different. Or even like, I think this is to a true, you know,

02:53:57.500 --> 02:54:01.040
Alexander Dugan, who I don't think he's, I don't think he's that close with Putin, actually.

02:54:01.040 --> 02:54:07.480
Like, I think people think he is. But I mean, it's, Putin is, I mean, that whole world is

02:54:07.480 --> 02:54:11.300
definitely trippier than we, than we, you know, realize. Like some of these guys are like,

02:54:11.720 --> 02:54:16.140
they're more esoteric than, you know, we might realize. And so it's like, how do you really

02:54:16.140 --> 02:54:22.180
understand how they make decisions at all? Right, right, right, right. Yeah. No, it's, it's,

02:54:22.180 --> 02:54:28.180
I think it's a little like our previous discussions on faith and mysticism and analyzing

02:54:28.180 --> 02:54:32.960
other countries and understanding what, more importantly than analyzing it is understanding

